Inapproximability of Maximum Weighted Edge Biclique and Its Applications

Jinsong Tan
Abstract

1 Introduction

Let G=(V1,V2,E)ğºsubscriptğ‘‰1subscriptğ‘‰2ğ¸G=(V_{1},V_{2},E) be an undirected bipartite graph. A biclique subgraph in GğºG is a complete bipartite subgraph of GğºG and maximum edge biclique (MEB) is the problem of finding a biclique subgraph with the most number of edges. MEB is a well-known problem and received much attention in recent years because of its wide range of applications in areas including machine learning [14], management science [16] and bioinformatics, where it is found particularly relevant in the formulation of numerous biclustering problems for biological data analysis [5, 2, 18, 19, 17], and we refer readers to the survey by Madeira and Oliveira [13] for a fairly extensive discussion on this. Maximum edge biclique is shown to be NP-hard by Peeters [15] via a reduction from 3SAT. Its approximability status, on the other hand, remains an open question despite considerable efforts [7, 8, 12] 111Note it might be easy to confuse the MEB problem with the Bipartite Clique problem discussed by Khot in [12]. Bipartite Clique, which also known as Balanced Complete Bipartite Subgraph [8], aims to maximize the number of vertices of a balanced subgraph whereas MEB aims to maximize the total weights on edges in a (not necessarily balanced) subgraph.. In particular, Feige and Kogan [8] conjectured that maximum edge biclique is hard to approximate within a factor of nÏµsuperscriptğ‘›italic-Ïµn^{\epsilon} for some Ïµ>0italic-Ïµ0\epsilon>0. In this paper, we consider a weighted formulation of this problem defined as follows

Definition 1

ğ’®ğ’®\mathcal{S}-Maximum Weighted Edge Biclique (ğ’®ğ’®\mathcal{S}-MWEB)

Instance: A complete bipartite graph G=(V1,V2,E)ğºsubscriptğ‘‰1subscriptğ‘‰2ğ¸G=(V_{1},V_{2},E) (throughout the paper, let Î·=mâ€‹aâ€‹xâ€‹{|V1|,|V2|}ğœ‚ğ‘šğ‘ğ‘¥subscriptğ‘‰1subscriptğ‘‰2\eta=max\{|V_{1}|,|V_{2}|\} and n=|V1|+|V2|ğ‘›subscriptğ‘‰1subscriptğ‘‰2n=|V_{1}|+|V_{2}|), a weight function wG:Eâ†’ğ’®:subscriptğ‘¤ğºâ†’ğ¸ğ’®w_{G}:E\rightarrow\mathcal{S}, where ğ’®ğ’®\mathcal{S} is a set consisting of both positive and negative integers.

Question: Find a biclique subgraph of GğºG where the sum of weights on edges is maximized.

A few comments are in order. First note it is not a lose of generality but a technical convenience to require the graph be complete, one can always think of an incomplete bipartite graph as complete where non-edges are assigned weight 0. Also note we require that both positive and negative weights be in ğ’®ğ’®\mathcal{S} at the same time because otherwise ğ’®ğ’®\mathcal{S}-MWEB becomes a trivial problem.

Our study of ğ’®ğ’®\mathcal{S}-MWEB is motivated by the problem of finding statistically significant biclusters in microarray data analysis in the SAMBA model [18] and the Minimum Description Length with Holes (MDLH) problem [3, 4, 10]; detailed discussion of the two problems can be found in Sect. 4. Our main technical contribution of this paper is to show that if ğ’®ğ’®\mathcal{S} satisfies the condition |minâ¡ğ’®maxâ¡ğ’®|âˆˆÎ©â€‹(Î·Î´âˆ’1/2)âˆ©Oâ€‹(Î·1/2âˆ’Î´)ğ’®ğ’®Î©superscriptğœ‚ğ›¿12ğ‘‚superscriptğœ‚12ğ›¿|\frac{\min\mathcal{S}}{\max\mathcal{S}}|\in\Omega(\eta^{\delta-1/2})\cap O(\eta^{1/2-\delta}), where Î´>0ğ›¿0\delta>0 is any arbitrarily small constant, then no polynomial time algorithm can approximate ğ’®ğ’®\mathcal{S}-MWEB within a factor of nÏµsuperscriptğ‘›italic-Ïµn^{\epsilon} for some Ïµ>0italic-Ïµ0\epsilon>0 unless ğ–±ğ–¯=ğ–­ğ–¯ğ–±ğ–¯ğ–­ğ–¯\mathsf{RP=NP}. This result enables us to answer open questions regarding the hardness of the SAMBA model and the MDLH problem. Since maximum edge biclique can be characterized as a special case of ğ’®ğ’®\mathcal{S}-MWEB with ğ’®={âˆ’Î·,1}ğ’®ğœ‚1\mathcal{S}=\{-\eta,1\}, the nÏµsuperscriptğ‘›italic-Ïµn^{\epsilon}-inapproximability result also provides interesting insights into the conjectured nÏµsuperscriptğ‘›italic-Ïµn^{\epsilon}-inapproximability [8] of maximum edge biclique.

The rest of the paper is organized in three sections. In Sect. 2, we present the main technical result by proving the aforementioned inapproximability of ğ’®ğ’®\mathcal{S}-MWEB. We give applications of this by answering hardness questions regarding two applied problems in Sect. 3. We conclude this work by raising a few open problems in the last section.

3 Two Applications

In this section, we describe two applications of the results establish in Sect. 3 by proving hardness and inapproximability of problems found in practice.

3.1 SAMBA Model is Hard

Microarray technology has been the latest technological breakthrough in biological and biomedical research; in many applications, a key step in analyzing gene expression data obtained through microarray is the identification of a bicluster satisfying certain properties and with largest area (see the survey [13] for a fairly extensive discussion on this).

In particular, Tanay et. al. [18] considered the Statistical-Algorithmic Method for Bicluster Analysis (SAMBA) model. In their formulation, a complete bipartite graph is given where one side corresponds to genes and the other size corresponds to conditions. An edges (u,v)ğ‘¢ğ‘£(u,v) is assigned a real weight which could be either positive or negative, depending on the expression level of gene uğ‘¢u in condition vğ‘£v, in a way such that heavy subgraphs corresponds to statistically significant biclusters. Two weight-assigning schemes are considered in their paper. In the first, or simple statistical model, a tight upper-bound on the probability of an observed biclusters in computed; in the second, or refined statistical model, the weights are assigned in a way such that a maximum weight biclique subgraph corresponds to a maximum likelihood bicluster.

3.2 Minimum Description Length with Holes (MDLH) is Hard

Bu et. al [4] considered the Minimum Description Length with Holes problem (defined in the following); the 2-dimensional case is claimed ğ–­ğ–¯ğ–­ğ–¯\mathsf{NP}-hard in this paper and the proof is referred to [3]. However, the proof given in [3] suffers from an error in its reduction333In Lemma 3.2.1 of [3], the reduction from CLIQUE to CEW is incorrect., thus whether MDLH is NP-complete remains unsettled. In this section, by employing the results established in the previous sections, we show that no polynomial time algorithm exists for MDLH, under the slightly weaker (than ğ–¯â‰ ğ–­ğ–¯ğ–¯ğ–­ğ–¯\mathsf{P\neq NP}) but widely believed assumption ğ–±ğ–¯â‰ ğ–­ğ–¯ğ–±ğ–¯ğ–­ğ–¯\mathsf{RP\neq NP}.

We first briefly describe the Minimum Description Length summarization with Holes problem; for a detailed discussion of the subject, we refer the readers to [3, 4].

Proof

We prove this by constructing a reduction from {âˆ’1,1}11\{-1,1\}-MWEB to Problem ğ’«ğ’«\mathcal{P} as follows: for the given input biclique G=(V1,V2,E)ğºsubscriptğ‘‰1subscriptğ‘‰2ğ¸G=(V_{1},V_{2},E), make Nğ‘N duplicates of V1subscriptğ‘‰1V_{1} and Nğ‘N duplicates of V2subscriptğ‘‰2V_{2}, where N=(|V1|+|V2|)2ğ‘superscriptsubscriptğ‘‰1subscriptğ‘‰22N=(|V_{1}|+|V_{2}|)^{2}. 4 Concluding Remarks

Maximum weighted edge biclique and its variants have received much attention in recently years because of it wide range of applications in various fields including machine learning, database, and particularly bioinformatics and computational biology, where many computational problems for the analysis of microarray data are closely related. To tackle these applied problems, various kinds of heuristics are proposed and experimented and it is not known whether these algorithms give provable approximations. In this work, we answer this question by showing that it is highly unlikely (under the assumption ğ–±ğ–¯â‰ ğ–­ğ–¯ğ–±ğ–¯ğ–­ğ–¯\mathsf{RP\neq NP}) that good polynomial time approximation algorithm exists for maximum weighted edge biclique for a wide range of choices of weight; and we further give specific applications of this result to two applied problems. We conclude our work by listing a few open questions.

1. We have shown that {Î˜â€‹(âˆ’Î·Î´),1}Î˜superscriptğœ‚ğ›¿1\{\Theta(-\eta^{\delta}),1\}-MWEB is nÏµsuperscriptğ‘›italic-Ïµn^{\epsilon}-inapproximable for Î´âˆˆ(âˆ’12,12)ğ›¿1212\delta\in(-\frac{1}{2},\frac{1}{2}); also it is easy to see that (i) the problem is in ğ–¯ğ–¯\mathsf{P} when Î´â‰¤âˆ’1ğ›¿1\delta\leq-1, where the entire input graph is the optimal solution; (ii) for any Î´â‰¥1ğ›¿1\delta\geq 1, the problem is equivalent to MEB, which is conjectured to be nÏµsuperscriptğ‘›italic-Ïµn^{\epsilon}-inapproximable [8]. Therefore it is natural to ask what is the approximability of the {âˆ’nÎ´,1}superscriptğ‘›ğ›¿1\{-n^{\delta},1\}-MWEB problem when Î´âˆˆ(âˆ’1,âˆ’12]ğ›¿112\delta\in(-1,-\frac{1}{2}] and Î´âˆˆ[12,1]ğ›¿121\delta\in[\frac{1}{2},1]. In particular, can this be answered by a better analysis of Lemma 3?

2. We are especially interested in {âˆ’1,1}11\{-1,1\}-MWEB, which is closely related to the formulations of many natural problems [1, 3, 4, 18]. We have shown that no polynomial time algorithm exists for this problem unless ğ–±ğ–¯=ğ–­ğ–¯ğ–±ğ–¯ğ–­ğ–¯\mathsf{RP=NP}, and we believe this problem is ğ–­ğ–¯ğ–­ğ–¯\mathsf{NP}-complete, however a proof has eluded us so far.
